The History of Violence meets Collateral with a dash of Locke? You got my attention.I'm so tempted to give this 4 stars. Yeah, there's a number of story details that won't hold up to much scrutiny (namely the implausible eccentricity of Cage's character), but I had a helluva lotta fun with it.Sympathy for the Devil is a two actor, limited location special that hinges on a fairly straightforward mystery. Thankfully the script keeps its cards close to the…

Visually delightful, curiously obtuse. Wes Anderson at perhaps his most cute, every frame art directed to blue and orange perfection. All to service a narrative that is often as difficult as it is dull. It does reward with a refreshingly uncharacteristic Jason Schwartzman performance.

Opening with a cheeky time bomb of a prologue that's one of the most outright engaging starts to a movie I've seen, Wild Tales is a jolt of cinematic dark comedy. Anthology films are tricky to pull off, and almost always succumb to a hit and miss nature. Here the quality rarely waivers thanks in large part to the assured hand of director Damián Szifron.Only the initial two stories truly deliver on the promise of the title. The rest,…

At the risk of a backhanded compliment, Air is the best version of an HBO Original movie. Ben Affleck as director plays it mostly safe and inbounds, only sporadically dipping into the playful style that Adam McKay would have sautéed every frame in, for better or worse. Damon gets to do his effortless star Moneyball performance and is pretty critical at times in holding the rope from this floating into parody. The divisive decision to not portray Michael Jordon on…

As someone who’s never struggled compartmentalizing an artist's life from their work, I accept that Ezra Miller can be both Kang the Conqueror of Hawaii and a talented, charismatic actor. Despite the maybe-now-in-retrospect manufactured early buzz, The Flash never stood a chance. Not with a crumbling, scatterbrained DCEU, a massive world reboot on the horizon, and a DOA press tour. Any yet, it's the most fun I've had watching a comic book movie in years. That said, this is one…

Save for Jeff Bridges' compellingly unusual choices and an effervescent early career Sandra Bullock, inferior to the original film in every way. This despite being helmed by the same director who no doubt caved to every studio whim against his better judgment. I wasn't exactly enamored by the 1988 Dutch version either but there's no questioning the power of its themes and how they are manifested in the ending, which this movie metaphorically pisses all over. Inexplicable Bill Simmons thought this was worthy of The Rewatchables.

Truly a tale of two halves.In the first we get probably the most restrained Guy Ritchie to date, leading the viewer from suspense laden combat to grueling cat and mouse escape. A warmly reserved Jake Gyllenhaal gets his best partner since End of Watch in Dar Salim, the duo engaged in a fierce stoicism competition where whoever loses, we win. It's a gripping 60ish minutes including one of my favorite sequences in a while.But old habits die hard.…

Taking pages from the aesthetics of John Wick's Continental, the single location big world building of Dredd, and the star laced ensemble of Bad Times at the El Royale, Hotel Artemis is as polished as is it derivitive. No, writer/director Drew Pearce isn't breaking the mold, but he does helm an engaging near-future yarn, where danger laced banter is shared by unsavaory types as a mysterious threat looms. Elevating the whole affair is Jodie Foster's snippy and world weary caretaker,…

Not even the Guardians of the Galaxy franchise is immune to this MCU Phase 5 slump. Clunky as hell, and bloated with a shaggy raccoon origin story that's basically Island of Misfit Toys if sadder. WHY IS EVERYONE YELLING? Guardians Vol. 2 was a colorful breath of fresh air in 2017 as it looked inward to its characters rather than outward towards the "who's got the latest Infinity Stone?" game. While uniquely self-contained (at the time) it still was tethered…

A fiercely committed Aubrey Plaza is let down by a confused script that can't decide if it wants to be a female riff on Cable Guy or a pitch black satire about the monster lurking behind every influencer facade. For a while Ingrid Goes West appears to be heading towards a clever about-face where an obsessive border-line psycho stalker is out-manipulated by her latest target. The movie flirts heavily with table turning our sympathy towards Plaza's Ingrid as Elizabeth Olsen's…

AMATWQ, as it's known in some circles (or not), starts chunkily in much the same way No Way Home did, something-something-ing its way into an inciting incident, in this case tossing everyone into the Quantum Realm which is basically John Carter meets the Star Wars Cantina scene. Cassie Lang, in the convo for the most irritating character in the MCU, spends the first act deriding her dad for "only" saving the entire world, and then stubbornly ignores all his advice…
